body:
@CharliePoole I made you a very small example of a case where ReSharper marks a test as pending:

``` csharp
using NUnit.Framework;

namespace PendingTests
{
    [TestFixture]
    public abstract class AbstractParent {
        [Test]
        public void TestMethod() {
            Assert.Pass();
        }
    }

    [TestFixture]
    public class TestFixture : AbstractParent {}
}
```

The `TestFixture` class inherits its tests from a parent class. With ReSharper, the code looks like this inside VS2015:
<img width="341" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1230950/13401963/7bf15338-df0e-11e5-8bca-699b536f08df.png">

I can run all the tests in `TestFixture` (including those in its parent classes – in this case `AbstractParent`'s `TestMethod`) using ReSharper by clicking the icon left of the class:
<img width="371" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1230950/13402031/c7e75602-df0e-11e5-9e81-ef75668b9c70.png">

That very breifly looks like this:
<img width="377" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1230950/13402086/051f4ca0-df0f-11e5-8172-6c6a6095500b.png">
Before changing to:
<img width="354" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1230950/13402128/2ec2e8be-df0f-11e5-801e-a3c98fdc7c94.png">

Notice that both the state, name and wall clock time changes and the test – now called `AbstractParent.TestMethod` – is marked as pending. The icon <img width="22" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1230950/13402447/98dd3424-df10-11e5-8edf-c54ab3f79667.png"> is for an "unknown" test. Removing `[TestFixture]` from either class has no effect. Neither does making `AbstractParent` a concrete class.

Whether this is an NUnit or a ReSharper issue is difficult for me to say.
